Craig's proposal has been roundly attacked, on the grounds that:  (1) it
is impossible to partially hide things [variation: a real hacker can
always find a way around any restriction], and (2) it is very difficult to
maintain a piece of the Internet without complete knowledge of all 
Internet hosts and gateways. To first order, these are probably both 
true.

Nevertheless, I foresee that there will be a real commercial 
requirement for some compartmentalization of the Internet.  If we don't
provide architected mechanisms to provide such isolation, then 
companies will resort to mail bridges or just not connect.  Or else
the vendors will go off and invent something.

Bob Braden

